{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500094"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1608"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1608"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.55,0.01,0,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1608"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40418"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1608"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1608"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25219"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"2637"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10352"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40418"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old woman presents with a painless swelling on her arm (Image). This has been present for several years, but has recently started to increase in size. She is otherwise well with no systemic features. Examination reveals a soft mass on palpation and a markedly reduced range of movement with no pain on active or passive movement. The area is not warm to touch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lipoma","Olecranon bursa","Gout","Septic arthritis","Epidermoid cyst"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary differentials for a swollen joint should always include \u003Cstrong\u003Egout\u003C/strong\u003E, pseudo-gout and \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst these would all be painful they are important differentials to exclude.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eolecranon bursa\u003C/strong\u003E is a clinical diagnosis. They may be preceded by trauma, however many cases can be idiopathic, or present with a more acute on chronic picture, as in this case. The bursa usually contains only a small volume of fluid - to help facilitate joint movement. Occasionally this can become inflamed (bursitis) or over-filled with fluid - as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth gout and septic arthritis are plausible options, however the stem lacks information that would make this diagnosis more likely, such as the lack of systemic features or risk factors such as a purine rich diet for gout. Additionally gout is intensely painful. Whilst it is not improbable for gout to affect an elbow, the stem makes it less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E would have a similar presentation to this stem, however compared to bursitis would be less likely to affect movement. Characteristic features of epidermoid cysts are a soft, skin coloured mass, however they rarely affect the elbow. Most commonly affecting the head, neck, trunk and genitals. It would be very unusual for an epidermoid cyst to get to this size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elipoma \u003C/strong\u003Eis a slow growing mass that has a rubbery texture on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Most olecranon bursae do not need any active intervention."],"references":["Nchinda NN, Wolf JM. Clinical Management of Olecranon Bursitis: A Review. J Hand Surg Am 2021; 46:501-06"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25219"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1608"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20119"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20119"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b1a7aa06-f191-41a6-9ae4-fa2eb3ce1142.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b1a7aa06-f191-41a6-9ae4-fa2eb3ce1142.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25219"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-11-17T16:58:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-11-17T16:58:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1608"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40418"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr